					<dt class="comment" id="comment-531768">
						<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-531768" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">83</a></span>
						<p><span class="comment_author">A H</span> <span class="comment_time">05.30.14 at 11:34 pm</span></p>
					</dt>
					<dd class="comment">
						<div class="format_text">
<p>As Bruce Wilder said above, r is a rate of return, it&#8217;s not a growth rate. </p>
<p>Piketty claims the economy tends toward a steady state in which the growth rate of capital is the same as the growth rate of output. This is determined by Piketty&#8217;s second &#8220;law&#8221;. </p>
<p>As I understand it, the crux of Piketty&#8217;s argument about r &gt; g, is that if g declines and r does not decline (and savings behavoir stays the same), then the steady state will be a much higher capital to output ratio than we have now.</p>
						</div>
					</dd>
		
